{
  "texts": [
    "In symbolic regression case, the encoder and the decoder do not share the same vocabulary because the decoder has a mixture of symbolic and numeric representations, while the encoder has only numeric representations.",
    "There exist two approaches to solving SR problems using transformers.",
    "First is the skeleton approach (Biggio et al. 2021; Valipour et al. 2021) where the transformer conducts the two-steps procedure: (1) the decoder predicts a skeleton f e, a parametric function that defines the general shape of the target expression up to a choice of constants, using the function class F and (2) the constants are fitted using optimization techniques such as the non-linear optimization solver BFGS.",
    "For example, if f = cos(2x 1) -0.1 exp(x 2), then the decoder predicts f e = cos(• x 1) -• exp(x 2) where • denotes an unknown constant.",
    "The second is an end-to-end (E2E) approach (Kamienny et al. 2022) where both the skeleton and the numerical values of the constants are simultaneously predicted."
  ]
}